<h1>2.5.4 Relative pronouns</h1>
<p>Status: draft (e.g.&nbsp;summary) ## Relevant postag codes:
<strong>Position and letters in postag string:</strong></p>
<ol type="1">
<li><p>part of speech: <strong>1st</strong>; letter: <strong>p</strong>
(pronoun)</p></li>
<li><p>number: <strong>3rd</strong>; letters: <strong>s</strong>
(singular), <strong>d</strong> (dual), <strong>p</strong>
(plural)</p></li>
<li><p>gender: <strong>7th</strong>; letters: <strong>m</strong>
(masculine), <strong>f</strong> (feminine), <strong>n</strong>
(neuter)</p></li>
<li><p>case: <strong>8th</strong>; letters: <strong>n</strong>
(nominative), <strong>g</strong> (genitive), <strong>d</strong>
(dative), <strong>a</strong> (accusative), <strong>v</strong>
(vocative)</p></li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Example postag string:</strong> p-s—nn- (pronoun, singular,
neuter, nominative)</p>
<h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
<p>The relative pronoun ὅς, ἥ, ὅ (hós, hḗ, hó, <em>who</em>,
<em>which</em>, <em>that</em>) is inflected in all numbers and
genders.</p>
<p>The declension table for the relative pronoun can be found in
<a data-link-newtab="" href="/smyth/body.1_div1.2_div2.6.html" data-url="smyth/body.1_div1.2_div2.6.html">Smyth §338</a>.</p>
<p>Smyth §339. “The indefinite or general relative pronoun ὅστις, ἥτις,
ὅ τι (hóstis, hḗtis, hó ti <em>whoever</em> (<em>any-who</em>,
<em>any-which</em>), <em>any one who</em>, <em>whatever</em>,
<em>anything which</em>, inflects each part (ὅς and τὶς)
separately.”</p>
<p>Smyth §2489. “Relative clauses are introduced by relative pronouns or
by relative adverbs of time, place , or manner (cp.&nbsp;340, 346), and refer
to an antecedent expressed or implied in the main clause.”</p>
<p>§2493. “ὅς (hós, <em>who</em>) and the other simple relatives
(e.g.&nbsp;οἷος, ὅσος – hoîos, <em>such as</em>, hósos <em>as much/many
as</em>) refer to a particular and individual person or thing.”</p>
